Information itself became a contested field. The administration shut down the U.S. Global Change Research Program\'92s climate website, cutting off public access to key reports and data. Homeland Security Secretary Kristi Noem and Trump threatened to prosecute CNN for reporting on the ICEBlock app, which alerts users to nearby ICE agents, and for coverage of a Pentagon assessment that questioned the effectiveness of strikes on Iran. Trump suggested forcing reporters to reveal their anonymous sources on Iran intelligence. The White House press secretary smeared Zohran Mamdani, the New York City mayoral candidate, as a \'93communist\'94 and falsely accused him of antisemitism. The administration sent a letter to Harvard University accusing it of violating the Civil Rights Act by failing to curb antisemitism and threatened to withdraw federal funding. The Social Security Administration circulated an email exaggerating the tax relief seniors would receive under the new law. These were not random misstatements. They were part of a pattern in which the state sought to control which facts remained visible and to punish institutions that carried unwelcome truths. Memory itself was being edited.\
