Against this backdrop, some forms of civic resistance persisted. Hundreds of protesters marched against Alligator Alcatraz. Over six hundred EPA employees, scientists, and academics signed a declaration warning that current policies undermined the agency\'92s mission to protect human health and the environment. Representative Hakeem Jeffries spoke for more than eight hours on the House floor, using his \'93magic minute\'94 to delay the vote and lay out the human costs of the bill. Constituents staged a die-in at Representative Fitzpatrick\'92s office to dramatize the stakes of healthcare cuts. State attorneys general sued over the loss of school-based mental health funds and the sharing of Medicaid data with immigration authorities. Courts exonerated six Chicago men wrongfully convicted in 1987 and prosecuted a Boulder hate-crime attacker and a New York doctor who had raped and filmed his patients. These acts did not stop the week\'92s main currents, but they kept alive alternative norms: that law should protect the vulnerable, that science should inform policy, that representation should mean more than obedience. The counter-story was weaker, but it was not silent.\
