Foreign policy developments, though outward-facing, were tightly bound to domestic power. Trump ordered large-scale airstrikes on Iranian nuclear facilities, deploying more than a hundred aircraft and bunker-busting bombs. He declared the operation a \'93spectacular success,\'94 while leaked intelligence suggested it had set back Iran\'92s program only by months. Iran responded by suspending cooperation with nuclear inspectors and, according to Trump\'92s own admission, by bombing a U.S. air base in Qatar with his tacit permission. The Pentagon paused some ammunition shipments to Ukraine and later halted them without notifying Kyiv or NATO allies, undermining earlier commitments. The administration pressured Israeli courts over Benjamin Netanyahu\'92s corruption trial, with Trump threatening to withhold aid if the proceedings continued, and an Israeli court postponed and then canceled hearings on classified grounds. A Lancet report estimated that cuts to USAID would cause more than fourteen million additional deaths worldwide by 2030. In each case, military and aid decisions served not only strategic aims but also domestic narratives of strength, grievance, and loyalty. Foreign lives and alliances were folded into home-front politics.\
