Even the week\'92s gestures toward beauty and conservation carried a double edge. Trump signed an order creating the President\'92s Make America Beautiful Again Commission, tasked with advising on conservation and access to public lands. Another order directed higher fees for foreign visitors to national parks while revoking a prior memorandum that had promoted diversity in park use. These moves came as environmental review laws were weakened in California, fossil fuels were favored over renewables in federal tax policy, and the EPA faced lawsuits over PFAS pollution from sewage sludge. The landscape was being curated in image and in law. The commission\'92s name evoked grandeur and restoration, even as the underlying policies tilted toward extraction and exclusion. The country was invited to admire the view while the rules beneath it changed.\
