Looking ahead from Week 24, several processes were already in motion. The Supreme Court had agreed to hear cases on coordinated campaign spending and transgender student sports bans in its next term, with the potential to further reshape campaign finance and civil rights. Federal courts had given the administration fourteen days to seek emergency relief from rulings blocking the asylum ban and TPS termination. The Election Assistance Commission scheduled a public meeting on voting system certification under updated guidelines. Environmental groups\'92 lawsuit over Alligator Alcatraz would test whether emergency powers could override environmental review. State attorneys general would press their challenges to Medicaid data sharing and school mental health cuts. These were not speculative risks. They were live dockets and scheduled hearings that would determine whether the week\'92s shifts hardened into precedent. The next moves were already on the calendar.\
\
By the close of the week, the Democracy Clock still read 7:49 p.m., but the day felt shorter. The law had been used less as a boundary and more as a tool. Congress had acted less as a forum and more as a stage. Policy had been driven less by broad consent than by concentrated wealth and fear. Citizenship had been sliced into tiers, with immigrants, naturalized citizens, and even some native-born Americans told, in effect, that their place was conditional. The security forces had been aligned more openly with the preservation of power than with the defense of people. Information and memory had been curated by those in office, with archives closed, websites shuttered, and critics threatened. Yet the very need for such measures\'97the lawsuits, the threats, the procedural contortions\'97also testified to the fact that resistance still existed. Courts could still say no. Protesters could still gather. Scientists could still sign their names.\
