Week 24 matters in the arc of the term because it shows how an elected government can, in a matter of days, convert campaign slogans into binding structure. The One Big Beautiful Bill is now law. Its tax cuts, its cuts to care, its billions for jails and walls, and its quiet clauses about data sharing and work requirements will shape lives long after the week\'92s headlines fade. The Supreme Court\'92s decisions on injunctions and immunity will govern not only this president but those who follow. The Everglades detention camp, the denaturalization memos, the threats to universities and media, and the arrests of officials will linger in institutional memory as examples of what is possible. The clock\'92s official time at the end of the period remains 7:49 p.m. That constancy should not comfort. It should remind us that democracies often erode not in a single leap, but in weeks like this one, when the law still moves, the courts still sit, the press still prints\'97and yet, step by step, power learns how to live with fewer limits.\
